<h2>Get tested for Chlamydia</h2>

<p>You should get tested if you have any <a href="condition#symptoms">symptoms of chlamydia</a> or you're <a href="condition#people-at-risk">at risk</a>.</p>

<div class="callout callout--attention">
    <p>The only way to know if you have <a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/chlamydia/symptoms/">chlamydia</a> is to get tested. You might have no symptoms.</p>
</div>

<p>You might be told to get tested 2 weeks after unprotected sex. This is because it can take 2 weeks for chlamydia to show up in a test.
</p>

<h2>How you'll be tested</h2>

<p>Samples will be taken from the areas that might be infected using one or more of the following methods:</p>

<ul>
    <li>swab inside the vagina, bottom or mouth using a cotton bud</li>
    <li>pee into a container</li>
</ul>

<p>Your samples will be sent to a lab and tested for chlamydia. You'll get your results by phone or text message.</p>

<p>If you see a health professional they'll also ask questions about your sexual activity and symptoms. This will help them decide what samples to take.</p>

<h2>Where you can get tested</h2>

<p>The best ways to get tested for chlamydia are to:</p>

<ul>
    <li>see a sexual health professional</li>
    <li>get a self-test kit from a pharmacy</li>
    <li>order a self-test kit online</li>
</ul>


